==German==
==Etymology==
Literally meaning "midweek", from [[Mitte]] "mid" and [[Woche]] "week" (assuming that the week starts on Sunday, the last day of the week being Saturday according to biblical tradition: God rested on the seventh day, Saturday).
===Proper noun===
'''Mittwoch''' ''m''
#[[Wednesday]], the day following [[Tuesday]] and preceeding [[Thursday]]. In German Mittwoch follows [[Dienstag]] and preceeds [[Donnerstag]].
#:''Mittwochs gehe ich immer schwimmen''

